ent options for people with mental health problems -- tEnabling futures for people with learning difficulties? Exploring employment realities behind the policy rhetoric -- tBarriers to labour market participation: the experience of Deaf and hard of hearing people -- tWork matters: visual impairment, disabling barriers and employment options -- tDisabled people and employment: the potential impact of European policy -- tMissing pieces: the voluntary and community sector’s potential for inclusive employment -- tProfessional barriers and facilitators: policy issues for an enabling salariat -- tDisabled people, the state and employment: historical lessons and welfare policy -- t‘Work’ is a four-letter word: disability, work and welfare -- tConclusions -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWorking futures? looks at the current effectiveness and future scope for enabling policy in the field of disability and employment. By addressing the current strengths and weaknesses of disability and employment policy, the book asks Is the dichotomy of 'work for those who can and support for those who cannot' appropriate to the lives of disabled people? Does current and recent policy reduce or reinforce barriers to paid employment? What lessons from other welfare regimes can we draw on to further disabled people's working futures? The book is original in bringing together a wide range of policy insights to bear on the question of disabled people's working futures. It includes analyses of recent policy initiatives as diverse as the Disability Discrimination Act 1995, Draft Disability Bill, the benefits system, New Deal for Disabled People, job retention policy, comparative disability policy, the role of the voluntary sector and 'new policies for a new workplace'. Contributions from academics, NGOs, the OECD and the disabled peoples' movement bring multiple theoretical, professional and user perspectives to the debates at the heart of the book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aManpower policyzGreat Britain. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxEmploymentxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / People with Disabilities.2bisacsh1 aBanks, Pauline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnes, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnes, Colin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aColeridge, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorden, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanieli, Ardha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibbs, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodley, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGradwell, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrove, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Jeannine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurstfield, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLunt, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeager, Nigel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMercer, Geof, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorouzi, Ghashem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearson, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrinz, Christop